was far superior to the system in France at the same period. He goes on to examine in detail the iron, textile, and pottery industries in each country, focusing on the effect of the quality of available transportation on the decisions of individual entrepreneurs and innovators. Szostak shows that in every case these industries were more highly developed in England than in France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndustrial revolutionzEngland. 0aIndustrial revolutionzFrance. 0aMetal tradezEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aMetal tradezFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aTextile industryzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aTextile industryzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aTransportationzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aTransportationzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356293640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562936423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562936/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles